      <title>Extinct Spell Lines, Anything To Be Done With Them?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=11674#M11674</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;There's a few spells left in their hayday that haven't been reproduced or upgraded, however do us service still today well enough. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Firstly there's Atone, mem blur has proven itself to be useful time and again to do some tricky stunts especially with the Sprinkler. With the level degradation of atone, what's the plausibility of seeing an upgrade at some point in the higher levels. It's a unique form of utility that's been sort of lost to the ages. Or was this spell dropped because it was deemed overpowered?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Mark of the Righteous, sure it's current incarnation was a fusion of our old previous lines. However it still stacks with Mark of the Martyr which combined make an 89 damage shield. Essentually it's an extinct stackible line which just decreases damage shield by 30. However is there any probability of making this a higher level spell line that does something unique on it's own? &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;One thought I had was correlating something of a sort of summons blades line from DnD, basically summons a bunch of morning stars to assail the opponent with a direct damage and a dot effect with the reverse DS aspect as well. But for starters while it would fit our summonsing weapons to assail our opponent, it would firstly not really fit the class in terms of DoTs and secondly it couldn't confer any sort of real dps which again wouldn't fit the class. Another mechanic to look at is a mitigation debuff, since we can already buff up mitigation. The one question I have though is on a raid mob, how much impact would a mitigation debuff really have? What else out there could be done to make a neo Mark of Righteous that could confer something unique and usefull to cross sections of play.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Divine Aura, will we ever receive an upgrade? I understand that there's relunctance for it, but it's been a cruct of our ability to drop aggro. Personally I think one of the detriments is that the short cast timer and long recast are something that is unecessary, 15 minutes as compared to a bard's 3 minutes. Could definately use a faster refresh, even if it's along the lines of a 5 minute reduction. Another aspect with Divine Barrier is the HP's healed, which is a joke but considering it's such a low level spell understandible. Perhaps another aspect to add in would be to offer self cures as well as a self hot in the aura mechanic, so could provide an extra round of cheap curing as well as avoid the dot problems associated with da but not totally stop certain ones. Basically taking the aspect from the ToTD discussions, it'd offer up some more uniqueness/utility to DA.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Wake of Tranquility, definately one of our most useful spells for pulling as it was an ae lull. It's never been upgraded at all, and it's definately one of our most useful utility spells. Is this spell line considered overpowered for clerics to have as it's been thusly restricted to only bards in the later expansions?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Greater Immobolization (short duration/fast cast) and Pretrifying Root (long duration, normal cast time) both have a resist adjust of -30 magic. However these don't seem to do what we need them to do, in terms of duality they firstly obviously don't serve as a well enough soloing (mob runs, dps goes down, and ect). Nor does it really have any effect on root park CC ability with high resists and short duration. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;One of the most popular suggestions is the anti-run/Call of the Chosonisque spell, thusly would increase soloing potential and allow our dps to be increased for a trade off in more amount of damage. Using either a symbol of our differing faith to cause a holy frenzy of the mob we're fighting or to use rhetoric and doctorine to incite our enemies to face us is definately within the realm of lore as well. The other aspect of root is the "normal root" since it offers up pseudo CC abilities. Two of the other priest classes has received a new knockback root along with rangers. The knockback root mechanic is something appealing, since firstly it confers to get the mob away from us and our group. But it also has a large solo application, in that since "tank rooting" is not applicible with dropping ward. If we're warding down something with a wanderer or trying to reroot something while trying to ward down something else we can take advantage of the knockback without us having to constantly move back to ward. We have two archaic root lines, what about junking the concept of their original casting limitations and going with a more cleric friendly playstyle ones. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;What are your thoughts?&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by Vjik on &lt;span class="date_text"&gt;10-30-2006&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="time_text"&gt;08:54 AM&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by Vjik on &lt;span class=date_text&gt;10-30-2006&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=time_text&gt;08:54 AM&lt;/span&gt;</description>
