      <title>Is Delay Death cancelling out/greatly lowering procs of Touch of the Divine?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=11467#M11467</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;font face="Arial" size="2"&gt;On &lt;a href="www.eqcleric.com" target=_blank&gt;www.eqcleric.com&lt;/a&gt; we've been discussing whether the Delay Death aa is causing Touch of the Divine to either fire less often, or not at all.&amp;nbsp; Anecdotal evidence seems to be showing that as you max out DD, your TotD fires less and less often.&amp;nbsp; Why would this be happening, if indeed it is?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font color="#ffffff" face="Arial" size="2"&gt;Let's look at why they might be interfering with each other...&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;TotD attempts to fire when your hp's reach zero. DD allows you to actually go below zero hp's. It very well could be that TotD attempts to fire, sees that DD has added hp's to you, or has somehow changed the death flagging on your toon, and therefor decides it doesn't need to fire as its conditions have not been met. It's kind of hard to explain, but I'm certain that you can see what I am getting at. When TotD does fire, it could be that it is doing so only on those occasions where you go below the additional death barrier that DD affords you. I think you really may be seeing something real happening.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Is this a case of two aa's interfering with one another a-la the AH/GoM bug that was finally fixed recently?&amp;nbsp; It makes sense that it might be occuring.&amp;nbsp; What has anyone else seen out in the field?&amp;nbsp; If a Dev is reading this could you possibly check and see if something like this is indeed happening?&amp;nbsp; We all know now that it is possible for an aa to block another aa from working correctly.&amp;nbsp; We're just curious and concerned that we've found another problem with the same underlying issue...&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
